  "prompt": "What is vector design?",
  "response": "Vector design, or vector graphics design, refers to the creation of images using mathematical formulas to represent shapes, lines, curves, and colors. Unlike raster graphics, which are made up of pixels and can lose quality when scaled up, vector graphics are resolution-independent. This means they can be resized to any dimension without losing clarity or detail. \n\nVector designs are typically created using software like Adobe Illustrator, CorelDRAW, or Inkscape. They are widely used in graphic design for creating logos, icons, typography, and any artwork requiring clean, scalable shapes. Common file formats for vector graphics include SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics), AI (Adobe Illustrator), and EPS (Encapsulated PostScript).\n\nKey features of vector design include:\n\n1. **Scalability**: Images can be scaled to any size without quality loss.\n2. **Editability**: Elements in vector files can be easily modified, whether it's changing colors, shapes, or positions.\n3. **Precision**: Suitable for designs requiring precise lines and geometric shapes, often used in technical illustrations and schematics.\n4. **Layering**: Allows for stacking of elements, which can be manipulated independently or as groups.\n\nOverall, vector design is essential for creating sharp, high-quality graphics that need to adapt to various sizes and applications, from business cards to large banners.",
